Exploring Sleeping Patterns Across Lifestyles¶

The essence of our well-being is strongly linked to sleep. As we continue to navigate the different stages of our lives, we expereince shifts in our professional life and adopt diverse lifestyles, however the significance of our sleep remains. Today, we will have the opportunity to expore sleeping patterns across a variety of factors.

What is healthy sleep, and why is it important to have it?¶

Healthy sleep refers to getting sufficient sleep duration as well as high sleep quality. Healthy sleep requires adequate sleep duration, appropriate timing, regularity, the absence of sleep disorders, and good quality.

The National Sleep Foundation recommends 7-9 hours of sleep per night for adults. [2]

Healthy sleep is important for cognitive functioning, mood, mental health, and cardiovascular, cerebrovascular, and metabolic health.[3]

Dataset Features¶

  1. Person ID: An identifier for each individual.
  2. Gender: The gender of the person (Male/Female).
  3. Age: The age of the person in years.
  4. Occupation: The occupation or profession of the person.
  5. Sleep Duration (hours): The number of hours the person sleeps per day.
  6. Quality of Sleep (scale: 1-10): A subjective rating of the quality of sleep, ranging from 1 to 10.
  7. Physical Activity Level (minutes/day): The number of minutes the person engages in physical activity daily.
  8. Stress Level (scale: 1-10): A subjective rating of the stress level experienced by the person, ranging from 1 to 10.
  9. BMI Category: The BMI category of the person (e.g., Underweight, Normal, Overweight).
  10. Blood Pressure (systolic/diastolic): The blood pressure measurement of the person, indicated as systolic pressure over diastolic pressure.
  11. Heart Rate (bpm): The resting heart rate of the person in beats per minute.
  12. Daily Steps: The number of steps the person takes per day.
  13. Sleep Disorder: The presence or absence of a sleep disorder in the person (None, Insomnia, Sleep Apnea).

The box plot shows that Females tend to have a longer sleep duration than Males.

Both Genders average around 7.2 hours of sleep, but Males tend to have a shorter sleep duration. The duartion of sleep also tends to vary more in Females than Males, where females have a high of 8.0 and males have a high of 7.7.

Let's check which occupation gets the most sleep.

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

plt.title("Duration of Sleep By Occupation")
plt.xticks(rotation = 80)
plt.xlabel("Occupation")
plt.ylabel("Duration of Sleep")
plt.show()

Looking at the Graph above, the occupation that gets the most sleep is Enigneering.

The second biggest group that has the most sleep is Doctor, followed by Nurses, Accountants and so on. The implication here is that Engineers face less levels of stress allowing them to have longer durations of sleep and even better quality as well.

Let us analyse wheteher quality of sleep is affected by stress.

We can see that sleep quality is inversely proportional to stress.

At lower stress levels, sleep quality ratings appear relatively consistent. However, as stress level rises, there's a noticeable decline in sleep quality.

The lineplot shows that with an increase in age, the sleep duration also increases. There is a difference in sleep duration and age based on gender.

The visualization shows similar trend patterns between men and women in ages between 30-45. Given the visualization, women had a decline in sleep duration between the age of 45 and 50. Consequently, the sleep duration continues to increase past the age of 50.

We can see that quality of sleep correlates positively with physical activity levels, while stress levels correlate negatively with sleep duration and quality of sleep. Interestingly, a small correlation exists between sleep duration and heart health indicators like heart rate and blood pressure.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, this analysis on sleep data across various factors like gender, age, occupation, lifestyle habits, and health metrics reveals some interesting insights. We found that on average, women tend to sleep longer than men. As age increases, sleep duration also improves up until late 40s, after which it declines before picking up again post 50 years. When observing occupations, engineers seem to get comparatively better sleep.

The analysis also surfaced a strong linkage between sleep quality and metrics like stress, activity levels, BMI, and blood pressure. People who sleep better are likely to have lower stress, be more active during the day, maintain a healthy BMI, and have lower blood pressure. On the other hand, poor sleep has an association with opposite effects on these markers.

Additionally, the prevalence of sleep disorders seems to correlate with BMI status - overweight and obese individuals are more likely to have conditions like insomnia and sleep apnea compared to those with normal BMI.
